Enclosing class:
JsXMLHttpRequest
public static class JsXMLHttpRequest.Member
extends DOM.XMLHttpRequest.Prototype.Member

An opaque class representing members of its enclosing opaque type.

Note that, this class is opaque but its constructors are all internal. This class and the subclasses of this class are used to declare either opaque public instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or the opaque public static fields of other opaque types while their constructors are used to define the fields inside opaque classes. Under either circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque fields of opaque types are resolved by re-compilers directly based on the field names.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be created in the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on operations accessing that kind of class objects. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque instance field declared by this class in Var.Member or its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
q.m
where m is the identifier of the field name and q is the identifier resolved from the instance of the enclosing member. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque static field declared by this class in opaque types other than Var.Member and its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
m
where m is the identifier of the field name. And re-compilers must report error on the access to opaque fields declared by this class under any other circumstances.

Field Detail

readyState

public final Value.Number.Member readyState

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object refers to a read-only integer value specifying the state of the HTTP request. The value begins at JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED or 0 when the JsXMLHttpRequest object is first created and increases to JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED or 4 when the complete HTTP response has been received. The five states are JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED, JsXMLHttpRequest.OPEN, JsXMLHttpRequest.SENT, JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING and JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED, each having an informal name associated with it.

The value of the property never decreases, unless JsXMLHttpRequest.abort() or JsXMLHttpRequest.open(String, String, Boolean, String, String) method is called on a request that is already in progress. Every time the value of the property increases, the JsXMLHttpRequest.onreadystatechange event handler is triggered.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED, JsXMLHttpRequest.OPEN, JsXMLHttpRequest.SENT, JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED, JsXMLHttpRequest.onreadystatechange, JsXMLHttpRequest.abort(), JsXMLHttpRequest.open(String, String), JsXMLHttpRequest.open(String, String, Boolean), JsXMLHttpRequest.open(String, String, Boolean, String, String)

responseText

public final Value.String.Member responseText

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object refers to a read-only string value specifying the body of the response, excluding headers, that has been received from the server so far, or the empty string if no data has been received yet. If readyState is less than JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, the property is the empty string. When readyState is JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, the property returns whatever portion of the response has been received so far. If readyState is JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED, the property holds the complete body of the response.

If the response includes headers that specify a character encoding for the body, that encoding is used. Otherwise, the Unicode UTF-8 encoding is assumed.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED, JsXMLHttpRequest.OPEN, JsXMLHttpRequest.SENT, JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

status

public final Value.Number.Member status

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object refers to a read-only integer value specifying the HTTP status code returned by the server, such as 200 for success and 404 for "Not Found" errors. Reading this property when readyState is less than JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING causes an error.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED, JsXMLHttpRequest.OPEN, JsXMLHttpRequest.SENT, JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED

statusText

public final Value.String.Member statusText

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object refers to a read-only string value specifying the HTTP status code of the request by name rather than by number. That is, it is "OK" when status is 200 and "Not Found" when status is 404. As with the status property, reading the property when readyState is less than JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING causes an error.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsXMLHttpRequest.UNINITIALIZED, JsXMLHttpRequest.OPEN, JsXMLHttpRequest.SENT, JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING, JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED
JavaScript:

responseXML

public final JsDocument.Member responseXML

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object is a read-only reference to the response to the request, parsed as XML and returned as a Document object. The property will be null unless all three of the following conditions are true:

  • readyState is JsXMLHttpRequest.LOADED.
  • The response includes a Content-Type header of "text/xml", "application/xml", or anything ending with "+xml" to indicate that the response is an XML document.
  • The response body consists of well-formed XML mark-up that can be parsed without errors.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

onreadystatechange

public final JsFunction.Member<?> onreadystatechange

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsXMLHttpRequest object is a reference to the event handler function invoked each time the readyState property changes. It may also be invoked multiple times while readyState is JsXMLHttpRequest.RECEIVING.

Since:
1.0

public JsXMLHttpRequest.Member(JsObject.Member q,

Internally constructs a member based on a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque instance fields declared in the declaring class of this constructor itself or its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or its subclasses are resolved by re-compilers directly to their names appending to the name resolved from the specified qualifying member with a dot in between.

Parameters:

mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:

JavaScript:
